# What are the types of load balancer in AWS
-> Classic load balancer
-> Application load balancer
-> Network load balancer [it used for transport layer, it work under TCP and UDP]
-> Gateway load balancer [it is used for security purpose]



# What is the difference between classic load balancer and application balancer
âš™ï¸ Classic Load Balancer (CLB)
Older generation load balancer (before ALB and NLB).
Works at Layer 4 (Transport) and Layer 7 (Application).
Supports one listener per load balancer, meaning it listens on one port (e.g., port 80 or 443) and forwards requests to backend instances on a fixed port.
You canâ€™t do advanced routing like based on URL path or hostname.

âœ… Example:
You have 3 EC2 instances running a web app on port 80.
CLB listens on port 80 â†’ sends traffic evenly to all 3 EC2 instances.

âš™ï¸ Application Load Balancer (ALB)
Modern load balancer (recommended for web apps and microservices).
Works at Layer 7 (Application Layer).
Supports multiple listeners and ports (for example, HTTP on port 80 and HTTPS on port 443).
Supports dynamic port mapping â€” especially useful for ECS or container-based apps, where each container might run on a different port.
Can route traffic intelligently using path-based or host-based rules.

âœ… Example:
Your ECS service runs multiple containers:
Container 1 â†’ port 32768
Container 2 â†’ port 32769
The ALB automatically maps incoming requests to whichever port your containers are using (this is dynamic port mapping).



-> Classic Load Balancer (CLB) supports a single listener per port and does not support dynamic port mapping.
-> Application Load Balancer (ALB) supports multiple listeners and ports, and allows dynamic port mapping for containers or services that use different ports â€” ideal for ECS or microservice architectures.



âš™ï¸ Network Load Balancer (NLB)
Designed for high-performance, low-latency applications.
Works at Layer 4 (Transport Layer) â€” handles TCP, UDP, and TLS traffic.
Can process millions of requests per second while maintaining ultra-low latency.
Supports static IP addresses and even Elastic IPs (EIPs) for predictable networking.
Best suited for use cases where performance, static IP, or handling non-HTTP(S) traffic matters.

âœ… Example:
Youâ€™re running a high-performance financial trading app or game server that uses TCP on port 443.
NLB listens on port 443 â†’ forwards requests directly to backend EC2 instances or containers (without modifying packets).
It maintains client IP visibility, so the backend knows the original source IP.

âš™ï¸ Gateway Load Balancer (GLB)
Specialized load balancer for network appliances like firewalls, intrusion detection systems (IDS), or deep packet inspection (DPI).
Works at Layer 3 (Network Layer) and Layer 4 (Transport Layer).
Combines a transparent network gateway with a load balancer â€” meaning traffic passes through it without needing app-level changes.
It distributes traffic across multiple virtual appliances while preserving the source and destination IPs.

âœ… Example:
You have 3 virtual firewall appliances running in EC2.
GLB receives traffic â†’ automatically distributes it across the 3 firewalls â†’ sends filtered/inspected traffic to your backend app servers.
This setup scales your network security layer automatically without reconfiguring routing


ðŸ” Quick Summary
# L3 Load Balancer (Network Layer)
Routes only based on IP address
Works at packet-level
Fastest but least intelligent

# L4 Load Balancer (Transport Layer)
Routes using IP + Port
Does not understand HTTP
Good for TCP/UDP apps

# L7 Load Balancer (Application Layer)
Understands HTTP
Can route using URLs, headers
Supports SSL termination
Best for modern web applications



